<paragraph blockId="72.[264,1324,604,950]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
Identification.—This species is easily recognized by its small size (&lt;
<quantity box="[1083,1152,604,630]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" unit="mm" value="7.0">7 mm</quantity>
in length) and appearance of a 
<taxonomicName box="[455,615,644,669]" class="Insecta" family="Dryophthoridae" genus="Rhodobaenus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[455,615,644,669]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Rhodobaenus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
rather than a typical 
<taxonomicName box="[858,999,644,669]" class="Insecta" family="Dryophthoridae" genus="Metamasius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[858,999,644,669]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Metamasius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Among 
<taxonomicName box="[1113,1255,644,669]" class="Insecta" family="Dryophthoridae" genus="Metamasius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1113,1255,644,669]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Metamasius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it has a characteristic color pattern (
<figureCitation box="[613,781,684,710]" captionStart="FIGURES 101 - 108" captionStartId="68.[264,382,1708,1731]" captionTargetBox="[281,1306,594,1686]" captionTargetId="figure@68.[281,1309,594,1686]" captionTargetPageId="68" captionText="FIGURES 101 - 108. Metamasius species. 101 - 102. Metamasius richdeboeri Anderson. 101. Dorsal habitus. 102. Lateral habitus. 103 - 104. Metamasius shchepaneki Anderson. 103. Dorsal habitus. 104. Lateral habitus. 105 - 106. Metamasius vaurieae Anderson. 105. Dorsal habitus. 106. Lateral habitus. 107 - 108. Metamasius wolfensohni Anderson. 107. Dorsal habitus. 108. Lateral habitus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/168667/files/figure.png" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
Figs. 
<number box="[679,781,684,710]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" value="105.5" valueMax="106.0" valueMin="105.0">105­106</number>
</figureCitation>
); a long narrow cylindrical evenly curved rostrum with the basal portion abruptly swollen immediately anterior to the eyes, the antennae inserted by about the width of the base of the scape from the anterior margin of the eyes (
<figureCitation box="[273,440,804,830]" captionStart="FIGURES 119 ­ 123" captionStartId="72.[264,382,1487,1511]" captionTargetBox="[277,1312,1009,1458]" captionTargetId="figure@72.[275,1313,1009,1460]" captionTargetPageId="72" captionText="FIGURES 119 ­ 123. Metamasius vaurieae Anderson. 119. Lateral view of head, male. 120. Lateral view of head, female. 121. Antenna. 122. Hind leg, male. 123. Pygidium, male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/156059/files/figure.png" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
Figs. 
<number box="[339,440,804,830]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" value="119.5" valueMax="120.0" valueMin="119.0">119­120</number>
</figureCitation>
); femora clavate, long and narrow, the hind femur almost reaching the apex of the pygidium (
<figureCitation box="[470,574,844,870]" captionStart="FIGURES 119 ­ 123" captionStartId="72.[264,382,1487,1511]" captionTargetBox="[277,1312,1009,1458]" captionTargetId="figure@72.[275,1313,1009,1460]" captionTargetPageId="72" captionText="FIGURES 119 ­ 123. Metamasius vaurieae Anderson. 119. Lateral view of head, male. 120. Lateral view of head, female. 121. Antenna. 122. Hind leg, male. 123. Pygidium, male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/156059/files/figure.png" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
Fig. 
<number box="[526,574,844,870]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" value="122.0">122</number>
</figureCitation>
); pygidium with the apical one­half sharply carinate and setose but not tumescent (
<figureCitation box="[494,598,884,910]" captionStart="FIGURES 119 ­ 123" captionStartId="72.[264,382,1487,1511]" captionTargetBox="[277,1312,1009,1458]" captionTargetId="figure@72.[275,1313,1009,1460]" captionTargetPageId="72" captionText="FIGURES 119 ­ 123. Metamasius vaurieae Anderson. 119. Lateral view of head, male. 120. Lateral view of head, female. 121. Antenna. 122. Hind leg, male. 123. Pygidium, male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/156059/files/figure.png" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
Fig. 
<number box="[550,598,884,910]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" value="123.0">123</number>
</figureCitation>
). In its small size and color pattern this species most closely resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[389,522,924,949]" class="Insecta" family="Dryophthoridae" genus="Metamasius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scutiger">
<emphasis box="[389,522,924,949]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">M. scutiger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Vaurie" authorityName="Vaurie" box="[579,952,924,950]" class="Insecta" family="Dryophthoridae" genus="Cactophagus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="condylus">
<emphasis box="[579,845,924,949]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Cactophagus condylus</emphasis>
(Vaurie)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
